#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:1
msgid "Python Wrappers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:3
msgid "Introduction"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:5
msgid ""
"This document is a reference for using VTK from Python. It is not a tutorial "
"and provides very little information about VTK itself, but instead describes "
"in detail the features of the Python wrappers and how using VTK from Python "
"differs from using VTK from C++.  It assumes that the reader is already "
"somewhat familiar with both Python and VTK."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:12
msgid "Background"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:14
msgid ""
"The Python wrappers are automatically generated from the VTK source code, "
"and for the most part, there is a one-to-one mapping between the VTK classes "
"and methods that you can use from Python and the ones that you can use from "
"C++.  More specifically, the wrappers are a package of Python extension "
"modules that interface directly to the VTK C++ libraries.  When you use VTK "
"through the wrappers, you are actually executing compiled C++ code, and "
"there is very little performance difference between VTK/C++ and VTK/Python."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:23
msgid "Installation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:25
msgid ""
"VTK for Python can be installed via either conda or pip, where the conda "
"packages is maintained on conda-forge, while the pip packages are maintained "
"by the VTK developers themselves.  If you are first getting started, then "
"pip is probably the most convenient way to install VTK for Python:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:30
msgid "pip install vtk\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:32
msgid ""
"This will provide a basic installation of VTK that includes all core "
"functionality, but which will not include some of the specialized VTK "
"modules that rely on external libraries.  Binary packages for VTK can also "
"be downloaded directly from https://www.vtk.org/download/."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:37
msgid ""
"Instructions for building VTK from source code are given in the file "
"[Documentation/dev/build.md][vtk-build] within the source repository."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:43
msgid "Importing"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:45
msgid ""
"VTK is comprised of over one hundred individual modules. Programs can import "
"just the modules that are needed, in order to reduce load time."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:48
msgid ""
"from vtkmodules.vtkCommonCore import vtkObject\n"
"from vtkmodules.vtkFiltersSources import vtkConeSource, vtkSphereSource\n"
"from vtkmodules.vtkRenderingCore import (\n"
"    vtkActor,\n"
"    vtkDataSetMapper,\n"
"    vtkRenderer,\n"
"    vtkRenderWindow\n"
")\n"
"import vtkmodules.vtkRenderingOpenGL2\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:58
msgid ""
"When getting started, however, it is hard to know what modules you will "
"need. So if you are experimenting with VTK in a Python console, or writing a "
"quick and dirty Python script, it is easiest to simply import everything.  "
"There is a special module called '`all`' that allows this to be done:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:63
msgid "from vtkmodules.all import *\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:65
msgid ""
"After importing the VTK classes, you can check to see which module each of "
"the classes comes from:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:68
msgid ""
"for c in vtkObject, vtkConeSource, vtkRenderWindow:\n"
"    print(f\"from {c.__module__} import {c.__name__}\")\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:71
msgid "The output is as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:73
msgid ""
"from vtkmodules.vtkCommonCore import vtkObject\n"
"from vtkmodules.vtkFiltersSources import vtkConeSource\n"
"from vtkmodules.vtkRenderingCore import vtkRenderWindow\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:77
msgid "Factories and Implementation Modules"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:79
msgid ""
"In the first 'import' example above, you might be wondering about this line:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:81
msgid "import vtkmodules.vtkRenderingOpenGL2\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:83
msgid ""
"This import is needed because `vtkRenderingOpenGL2` provides the OpenGL "
"implementations of the classes in `vtkRenderingCore`.  To see this in "
"action, open a new Python console and do the following:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:87
msgid ""
">>> from vtkmodules.vtkRenderingCore import vtkRenderWindow\n"
">>> renwin = vtkRenderWindow()\n"
">>> type(renwin)\n"
"<class 'vtkmodules.vtkRenderingCore.vtkRenderWindow'>\n"
">>>\n"
">>> import vtkmodules.vtkRenderingOpenGL2\n"
">>> renwin2 = vtkRenderWindow()\n"
">>> type(renwin2)\n"
"<class 'vtkmodules.vtkRenderingOpenGL2.vtkXOpenGLRenderWindow'>\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:97
msgid ""
"After `vtkRenderingOpenGL2` has been imported, the `vtkRenderWindow()` "
"constructor magically starts returning a different type of object. This "
"occurs because `vtkRenderWindow` is a *factory* class, which means that the "
"kind of object it produces can be overridden by an *implementation* class.  "
"In order for the implementation class to do the override, all that is "
"necessary is that its module is imported.  To make things even more "
"confusing, `vtkRenderingOpenGL2` is not the only module that contains "
"implementations for the factory classes in `vtkRenderingCore`.  The "
"following modules are often needed, as well:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:107
msgid ""
"import vtkmodules.vtkInteractionStyle\n"
"import vtkmodules.vtkRenderingFreeType\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:110
msgid ""
"Although you only need implementations for the factory classes that you use, "
"it can be hard to know which classes are factory classes, or what modules "
"contain implementations for them.  Also, it can be difficult to even know "
"what classes you are using, since many VTK classes make use of other VTK "
"classes.  An example of this is `vtkDataSetMapper`, which internally uses "
"`vtkPolyDataMapper` to do the rendering.  So even though `vtkDataSetMapper` "
"is not a factory class, it needs an OpenGL implementation for "
"`vtkPolyDataMapper`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:118
msgid ""
"The simplest approach is to import all the important implementation modules "
"into your program, even if you are not certain that you need them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:120
msgid ""
"For `vtkRenderingCore`, `import vtkRenderingOpenGL2, vtkRenderingFreeType, "
"vtkInteractionStyle`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:121
msgid "For `vtkRenderingVolume`, `import vtkRenderingVolumeOpenGL2`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:122
msgid "For `vtkCharts`, `import vtkContextOpenGL2`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:124
msgid "Classic VTK Import"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:126
msgid ""
"There are many VTK programs that still import the '`vtk`' module, which has "
"been available since VTK 4.0, rather than using the '`vtkmodules`' package "
"that was introduced in VTK 8.2:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:130
msgid "import vtk\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:132
msgid ""
"The advantage (and disadvantage) of this is that it imports everything.  It "
"requires just one import statement for all of VTK, but it can be slow "
"because VTK has grown to be very large over the years."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:136
msgid ""
"Also note that, between VTK 8.2 and VTK 9.2.5, the use of the `vtk` module "
"would confuse the auto-completion features of IDEs such as PyCharm.  This "
"was fixed in VTK 9.2.6.  For 9.2.5 and earlier, the following can be used:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:140
msgid "import vtkmodules.all as vtk\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:142
msgid ""
"From the programmer's perspective, this is equivalent to '`import vtk`'."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:144
msgid "VTK Classes and Objects"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:146
msgid "Classes Derived from vtkObjectBase"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:148
msgid ""
"In C++, classes derived from `vtkObjectBase` are instantiated by calling "
"`New()`.  In Python, these classes are instantiated by simply calling the "
"constructor:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:152
msgid "o = vtkObject()\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:154
msgid ""
"For factory classes, the returned object's type might be a subtype of the "
"class.  This occurs because the Python wrappers are actually calling `New()` "
"for you, which allows the VTK factory overrides to occur:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:158
msgid ""
">>> a = vtkActor()\n"
">>> type(a)\n"
"<class 'vtkmodules.vtkRenderingOpenGL2.vtkOpenGLActor'>\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:162
msgid ""
"When you create a VTK object in Python, you are in fact creating two "
"objects: a C++ object, and a Python object that holds a pointer to the C++ "
"object.  The `repr()` of the object shows the memory address of the C++ "
"object (in parentheses) and of the Python object (after the '`at`'):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:167
msgid ""
">>> a = vtkFloatArray()\n"
">>> a\n"
"<vtkmodules.vtkCommonCore.vtkFloatArray(0x5653a6a6f700) at 0x7f0e7aecf5e0>\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:171
msgid ""
"If you call `str()` or `print()` on these objects, the wrappers will call "
"the C++ `PrintSelf()` method.  The printed information can be useful for "
"debugging:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:174
msgid ""
">>> o = vtkObject()\n"
">>> print(o)\n"
"vtkObject (0x55858308a210)\n"
"  Debug: Off\n"
"  Modified Time: 85\n"
"  Reference Count: 1\n"
"  Registered Events: (none)\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:182
msgid "Other Classes (Special Types)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:184
msgid ""
"VTK also uses several classes that aren't derived from `vtkObjectBase`.  The "
"most important of these is `vtkVariant`, which can hold any type of object:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:187
msgid ""
">>> v1 = vtkVariant('hello')\n"
">>> v1\n"
"vtkmodules.vtkCommonCore.vtkVariant('hello')\n"
">>> v2 = vtkVariant(3.14)\n"
">>> v2\n"
"vtkmodules.vtkCommonCore.vtkVariant(3.14)\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:194
msgid ""
"The wrapping of these classes is fully automatic, but is done in a slightly "
"different manner than `vtkObjectBase`-derived classes.  First, these classes "
"have no `New()` method, and instead the public C++ constructors are wrapped "
"to create an equivalent Python constructor.  Second, the Python object "
"contains its own copy of the C++ object, rather than containing just a "
"pointer to the C++ object.  The vast majority of these classes are "
"lightweight containers and numerical types.  For example, `vtkQuaterniond`, "
"`vtkRectf`, `vtkColor4ub`, etc.  Many of them are actually class templates, "
"which are discussed below."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:204
msgid ""
"When you apply `print()` or `str()` to these objects, the `operator<<` of "
"the underlying C++ object is used to print them.  For `repr()`, the name of "
"the type name is printed, followed by the `str()` output in prentheses.  The "
"result looks similar to a constructor, though it might look strange "
"depending on what `operator<<` produces."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:210
msgid ""
">> v = vtkVariant()\n"
">> print(repr(v))\n"
"vtkmodules.vtkCommonCore.vtkVariant((invalid))\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:214
msgid "Class Templates"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:216
msgid ""
"There are several C++ templates in VTK, which can be tricky to use from the "
"wrappers since the Python language has no real concept of templates.  The "
"wrappers wrap templates as dictionary-like objects that map the template "
"parameters to template instantiations:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:221
msgid ""
">>> vtkSOADataArrayTemplate\n"
"<template vtkCommonCorePython.vtkSOADataArrayTemplate>\n"
">>> vtkSOADataArrayTemplate.keys()\n"
"['char', 'int8', 'uint8', 'int16', 'uint16', 'int32', 'uint32', 'int',\n"
"'uint', 'int64', 'uint64', 'float32', 'float64']\n"
">>> c = vtkSOADataArrayTemplate['float64']\n"
">>> c\n"
"<class 'vtkmodules.vtkCommonCore.vtkSOADataArrayTemplate_IdE'>\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:230
msgid ""
"The wrappers instantiate the C++ template for a few useful types, as "
"indicated by the `keys()` of the template.  The Python type name also has a "
"suffix (the '`IdE`') that indicates the template parameters in a compressed "
"form according to IA64 C++ ABI name mangling rules, even when VTK is built "
"with a compiler that does not use the IA64 ABI natively."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:236
msgid ""
"Objects are created by first instantiating the template, and then "
"instantiating the class:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:239
msgid ""
">>> a = vtkSOADataArrayTemplate['float32']()\n"
">>> a.SetNumberOfComponents(3)\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:242
msgid ""
"In the case of multiple template parameters, the syntax can look rather "
"complicated, but really it isn't all that bad.  For example, constructing a "
"`vtkTuple<double,4>` in Python looks like this, with the template args in "
"square brackets and the constructor args in parentheses:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:247
msgid ""
">>> vtkTuple['float64',4]([1.0, 2.0, 3.0, 4.0])\n"
"vtkmodules.vtkCommonMath.vtkTuple_IdLi4EE([1.0, 2.0, 3.0, 4.0])\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:250
msgid ""
"The type names are the same as numpy's dtypes: `bool`, `int8`, `uint8`, "
"`int16`, `uint16`, `int32`, `uint32`, `int64`, `uint64`, `float32`, and "
"`float64`.  Since `int64` is '`long long`', `int` is used for `long`.  Also "
"see [Template Keys](#template-keys) in [Advanced Topics](#internals-and-"
"advanced-topics)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:256
msgid "Method Calls"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:258
msgid ""
"When VTK methods are called from Python, conversion of all parameters from "
"Python to C++ occurs automatically.  That is, if the C++ method signature "
"expects an integral type, you can pass a Python `int`, and if C++ expects a "
"floating-point type, you can pass a Python `float` (or any type that allows "
"implicit conversion to `float`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:264
msgid ""
"For C++ '`char`' parameters, which are rarely used in VTK, you must pass a "
"string with a length of 1. For unicode, the code must fit into eight bits "
"(either ASCII, or within the Latin-1 Supplement block).  A null character is "
"represented by '\\\\0', or equivalently `chr(0)`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:269
msgid ""
"A Python `tuple`, `list`, or any other Python sequence can be passed to a "
"VTK method that requires an array or `std::vector` in C++:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:272
msgid ""
">>> a = vtkActor()\n"
">>> p = (100.0, 200.0, 100.0)\n"
">>> a.SetPosition(p)\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:276
msgid ""
"If the method is going to modify the array that you pass as a parameter, "
"then you must pass a Python `list` that has the correct number of slots to "
"accept the returned values.  If you try this with a `tuple`, you will get a "
"`TypeError` because `tuple` is immutable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:281
msgid ""
">>> z = [0.0, 0.0, 0.0]\n"
">>> vtkMath.Cross((1,0,0),(0,1,0),z)\n"
">>> print(z)\n"
"[0.0, 0.0, 1.0]\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:286
msgid ""
"For multi-dimensional array parameters, you can either use a nested list, or "
"you can use numpy array with the correct shape."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:289
msgid ""
"If the C++ method returns a pointer to an array, then in Python the method "
"will return a tuple if the wrappers know the size of the array.  In most "
"cases, the size is hinted in the header file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:293
msgid ""
">>> a = vtkActor()\n"
">>> print(a.GetPosition())\n"
"(0.0, 0.0, 0.0)\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:297
msgid ""
"Finally, Python `None` is treated the same as C++ `nullptr`, which allows "
"you to pass null objects and null strings:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:300
msgid ""
">>> a = vtkActor()\n"
">>> a.SetMapper(None)\n"
">>> print(a.GetMapper())\n"
"None\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:305
msgid "Wrappable and Unwrappable Methods"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:307
msgid ""
"A method cannot be used from Python if its C++ parameters or return type "
"cannot be converted to or from Python by the wrappers, or if the method is "
"templated.  Common non-convertible types include `std::ostream`, `std::"
"istream`, and all STL container types except for `std::vector` (see below), "
"and any non-trivial pointer type or any pointer to an object whose class is "
"not derived from `vtkObjectBase`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:314
msgid "The wrappable parameter types are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:315
msgid "`char`, wrapped as a single ASCII character in a Python `str`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:316
msgid "`signed char` and `unsigned char`, wrapped as Python `int`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:317
msgid "`short`, `int`, `long` and `long long`, wrapped as Python `int`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:318
msgid "`unsigned short` to `unsigned long long`, wrapped as Python `int`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:319
msgid "`float` and `double`, wrapped as Python `float`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:320
msgid "`size_t` and `ssize_t`, wrapped as Python `int`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:321
msgid "`std::string`, wrapped as Python `str` via utf-8 encoding/decoding"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:322
msgid "typedefs of all the above, for any typedef defined in a VTK header file"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:323
msgid ""
"`std::vector<T>` where `T` is one of the above, as Python `tuple` or `list`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:324
msgid "`const T&` where `T` is any of the above, wrapped as described above"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:325
msgid "`T[N]` where `T` is a fundamental type, as Python `tuple` or `list`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:326
msgid "`T[N][M]` where `T` is a fundamental type, as nested `tuple` or `list`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:327
msgid "`T*` where `T` is a fundamental type, as `tuple` or `list`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:328
msgid "`vtkObjectBase*` and derived types, as their respective Python type"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:329
msgid "`vtkSmartPointer<T>` as the Python vtkObjectBase-derived type `T`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:330
msgid "`std::vector<vtkSmartPointer<T>>` as a sequence of objects of type `T`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:331
msgid ""
"`const std::vector<vtkSmartPointer<T>>` as a sequence of objects of type `T`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:332
msgid ""
"other wrapped classes (like `vtkVariant`), but not pointers to these types"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:333
msgid "`char*`, as Python `str` via utf-8 encoding/decoding"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:334
msgid "`void*`, as Python buffer (e.g. `bytes` or `bytearray`)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:335
msgid ""
"the parameter list `(void (*f)(void*), void*)` as a Python callable type"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:337
msgid ""
"References like `int&` and `std::string&` are wrapped via a reference proxy "
"type as described in the [Pass by Reference](#pass-by-reference) section "
"below.  Non-const references to `std::vector<T>` and other mutable types do "
"not use a proxy, but instead require that a mutable Python object is passed, "
"for example a `list` rather than a `tuple`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:343
msgid ""
"A `void*` parameter can accept a pointer in two different ways: either from "
"any Python object that supports the Python buffer protocol (this includes "
"all numpy arrays along with the Python bytes and bytearray types), or from a "
"string that contains a mangled pointer of the form '`_hhhhhhhhhhhh_p_void`' "
"where '`hhhhhhhhhhhh`' is the hexadecimal address.  Return-value `void*` "
"will always be a string containing the mangled pointer."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:350
msgid ""
"Also, a `T*` parameter for fundamental type `T` can accept a buffer object, "
"if and only if it is annotated with the `VTK_ZEROCOPY` hint in the header "
"file. With this hint, a numpy array of `T` can be passed to a `T*` parameter "
"and the VTK method will directly access the memory buffer of the array.  "
"Hence the name 'zerocopy', which indicates no copying is done, and that "
"direct memory access is used."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:357
msgid ""
"The `vtkObject::AddObserver()` method has a special wrapping, as discussed "
"in the [Observer Callbacks](#observer-callbacks) section below."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:360
msgid "Conversion Constructors"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:362
msgid ""
"If a wrapped type has constructor that takes one parameter, and if that "
"constructor is not declared '`explicit`', then the wrappers will "
"automatically use that constructor for type conversion to the parameter "
"type.  The wrappers ensure that this conversion occurs in Python in the same "
"manner that it is expected to occur in C++."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:368
msgid ""
"For example, `vtkVariantArray` has a method `InsertNextItem(v:vtkVariant)`, "
"and `vtkVariant` has a constructor `vtkVariant(x:int)`.  So, you can do this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:371
msgid ">>> variantArray.InsertNextItem(1)\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:373
msgid ""
"The wrappers will automatically construct a `vtkVariant` from '`1`', and "
"will then pass it as a parameter to `InsertNextItem()`.  This is a feature "
"that most C++ programmers will take for granted, but Python users might find "
"it surprising."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:378
msgid "Overloaded Methods"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:380
msgid ""
"If you call a VTK method that is overloaded, the Python wrappers will choose "
"the overload that best matches the supplied arguments.  This matching takes "
"into account all allowed implicit conversions, such as int to float or any "
"conversion constructors that are defined for wrapped objects."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:385
msgid ""
"Some overloads will be unavailable (not wrapped) either because they are "
"unwrappable as per the criteria described above, or because they are "
"shadowed by another overload that is always preferable.  A simple example of "
"this is any methods that is overloaded on C++ `float` and `double`.  The "
"Python `float` type is a perfect match C++ `double`, therefore the `float` "
"overload is not wrapped."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:392
msgid "Static Methods"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:394
msgid "A static method can be called without an instance.  For example,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:396
msgid "vtkObject.SetGlobalWarningDisplay(1)\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:398
msgid ""
"Some VTK classes, like vtkMath, consist solely of static methods.  For "
"others, like `vtkMatrix4x4`, most of the non-static methods have static "
"overloads. Within Python, the only way to tell if a VTK method is static "
"(other than trying it) is to look at its docstring."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:403
msgid "Unbound Methods"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:405
msgid ""
"When a non-static method is called on the class, rather than on an instance, "
"it is called an unbound method call.  An unbound method call must provide "
"'self' as the first argument, where 'self' is an instance of either the "
"class or a subclass."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:410
msgid ""
"w = vtkRenderWindow()\n"
"vtkWindow.Render(w)\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:413
msgid ""
"In other words, the wrappers translate Python unbound method calls into C++ "
"unbound method calls.  These are useful when deriving a Python class from a "
"wrapped VTK class, since they allow you to call any base class methods that "
"have been overridden in the subclass."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:418
msgid "Operator Methods"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:420
msgid ""
"For special classes (the ones not derived from `vtkObjectBase`), some useful "
"C++ operators are wrapped in python.  The '`[]`' operator is wrapped for "
"indexing and item assignment, but because it relies on hints to guess which "
"indices are out-of-bounds, it is only wrapped for `vtkVector` and related "
"classes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:426
msgid ""
"The comparison operators '`<`' '`<=`' '`==`' '`>=`' '`>`' are wrapped for "
"all classes that have these operators in C++.  These operators allow sorting "
"of `vtkVariant` objects with Python."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:430
msgid ""
"The '`<<`' operator for printing is wrapped and is used by the python "
"`print()` and `str()` commands."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:433
msgid "Strings and Bytes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:435
msgid ""
"VTK uses both `char*` and `std::string` for strings.  As far as the wrappers "
"are concerned, these are equivalent except that the former can be `nullptr` "
"(`None` in Python).  For both, the expected encoding is ASCII or utf-8."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:439
msgid ""
"In Python, either `str` or `bytes` can be used to store strings, and both of "
"these can be passed to VTK methods that require `char*` or `std::string` (or "
"the legacy `vtkStdString`).  A `str` object is passed to VTK as utf-8, while "
"a `bytes` object is passed as-is."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:444
msgid ""
"When a VTK method returns a string, it is received in Python as a `str` "
"object if it is valid utf-8, or as a `bytes` object if not.  The caller "
"should check the type of the returned object (`str`, `bytes`, or perhaps "
"`None`) if there is any reason to suspect that non-utf-8 text might be "
"present."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:449
msgid "STL Containers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:451
msgid ""
"VTK provides conversion between `std::vector` and Python sequences such as "
"`tuple` and `list`.  If the C++ method returns a vector, the Python method "
"will return a tuple:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:455
msgid ""
"C++: const std::vector<std::string>& GetPaths()\n"
"C++: std::vector<std::string> GetPaths()\n"
"Python: GetPaths() -> Tuple[str]\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:459
msgid ""
"If the C++ method accepts a vector, then the Python method can be passed any "
"sequence with compatible values:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:462
msgid ""
"C++: void SetPaths(const std::vector<std::string>& paths)\n"
"C++: void SetPaths(std::vector<std::string> paths)\n"
"Python: SetPaths(paths: Sequence[str]) -> None\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:466
msgid ""
"Furthermore, if the C++ method accepts a non-const vector reference, then "
"the Python method can be passed a mutable sequence (e.g. `list`):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:469
msgid ""
"C++: void GetPaths(std::vector<std::string>& paths)\n"
"Python: GetPaths(paths: MutableSequence[str]) -> None\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:472
msgid ""
"The value type of the `std::vector<T>` must be `std::string` or a "
"fundamental numeric type such as `double` or `int` (including `signed char` "
"and `unsigned char` but excluding `char`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:476
msgid "Smart pointers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:478
msgid ""
"The wrappers will automatically convert between C++ `vtkSmartPointer<T>` and "
"objects of type `T` (or `None`, if the smart pointer is empty):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:481
msgid ""
"C++: vtkSmartPointer<vtkObject> TakeObject()\n"
"Python: TakeObject() -> vtkObject\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:484
msgid ""
"In other words, in Python the smart pointer doesn't look any different from "
"the object it points to.  Under the hood, however, the wrappers understand "
"that the smart pointer carries a reference to the object and will take "
"responsibility for deleting that reference."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:489
msgid ""
"A C++ method can return a vector of smart pointers, which will be seen in "
"Python as a tuple of objects:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:492
msgid ""
"C++: std::vector<vtkSmartPointer<vtkObject>> GetObjects()\n"
"Python: GetObject() -> Tuple[vtkObject]\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:495
msgid ""
"If a C++ method expects `std::vector<vtkSmartPointer<T>>` as a parameter, "
"the wrappers will automatically construct the vector from any sequence that "
"is passed from Python.  The objects in the sequence must be of type `T` (or "
"a subclass of `T`, or `None`).  If not, a `TypeError` will be raised."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:500
msgid "Pass by Reference"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:502
msgid ""
"Many VTK methods use pass-by-reference to return values back to the caller. "
"Calling these methods from Python requires special consideration, since "
"Python's `str`, `tuple`, `int`, and `float` types are immutable.  The "
"wrappers provide a '`reference`' type, which is a simple container that "
"allows pass-by-reference."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:508
msgid ""
"For example, consider the following C++ method that uses pass-by-reference:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:510
msgid ""
"void GetCellAtId(vtkIdType cellId, vtkIdType& cellSize, vtkIdType const*& "
"cellPoints)\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:512
msgid ""
"It requires a reference to `vtkIdType` (a Python `int`), and to `vtkIdType "
"const*` (a tuple of `int`s).  So we can call this method as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:516
msgid ""
">>> from vtkmodules.vtkCommonCore import reference\n"
">>> from vtkmodules.vtkCommonDataModel import vtkCellArray\n"
">>>\n"
">>> # Build a cell array\n"
">>> a = vtkCellArray()\n"
">>> a.InsertNextCell(3, (1, 3, 0))\n"
">>>\n"
">>> # Create the reference objects\n"
">>> n = reference(0)\n"
">>> t = reference((0,))\n"
">>>\n"
">>> # Call the pass-by-reference method\n"
">>> a.GetCellAtId(0, n, t)\n"
">>>\n"
">>> n.get()\n"
"3\n"
">>> t.get()\n"
"(1, 3, 0)\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:535
msgid "Some important notes when using pass-by-reference:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:536
msgid ""
"The reference constructor must be given a value of the desired type. The "
"method might use this value or might ignore it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:538
msgid ""
"Calling the `get()` method of the reference is usually unnecessary, because "
"the reference already supports the interface protocols of the object that it "
"contains."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:542
msgid "Preconditions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:544
msgid ""
"One very real concern when using VTK from Python is that the parameters that "
"you pass to a method might cause the program to crash.  In particular, it is "
"very easy to pass an index that causes an out-of-bounds memory access, since "
"the C++ methods don't do bounds checking.  As a safety precaution, the "
"wrappers perform the bounds check before the C++ method is called:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:550
msgid ""
">>> a = vtkFloatArray()\n"
">>> a.GetValue(10)\n"
"Traceback (most recent call last):\n"
"  File \"<stdin>\", line 1, in <module>\n"
"ValueError: expects 0 <= id && id < GetNumberOfValues()\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:556
msgid ""
"All precondition checks raise a `ValueError` if they fail, since they are "
"checks on the values of the parameters.  The wrappers don't know if C++ is "
"using the parameter as an index, so `IndexError` is not used."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:560
msgid ""
"Currently the only way to find out if a method has preconditions is to look "
"at the declaration of the method in the C++ header file to see if it has a "
"`VTK_EXPECTS` hint."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:564
msgid "Observer Callbacks"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:566
msgid ""
"Similar to what can be done in C++, a Python function can be called each "
"time a VTK event is invoked on a given object.  In general, the callback "
"function should have the signature `func(obj:vtkObject, event:str)`, or "
"`func(self, obj:vtkObject, event:str)` if it is a method of a class."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:571
msgid ""
">>> def onObjectModified(object, event):\n"
">>>     print('object: %s - event: %s' % (object.GetClassName(), event))\n"
">>>\n"
">>> o = vtkObject()\n"
">>> o.AddObserver(vtkCommand.ModifiedEvent, onObjectModified)\n"
"1\n"
">>> o.Modified()\n"
"object: vtkObject - event: ModifiedEvent\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:581
msgid "Call Data"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:583
msgid ""
"In case there is a 'CallData' value associated with an event, in C++, you "
"have to cast it from `void*` to the expected type using `reinterpret_cast`. "
"The equivalent in python is to add a `CallDataType` attribute to the "
"associated python callback method. The supported `CallDataType` values are "
"`VTK_STRING`, `VTK_OBJECT`, `VTK_INT`, `VTK_LONG`, `VTK_DOUBLE`, and "
"`VTK_FLOAT`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:590
msgid ""
"The following example uses a function as a callback, but a method or any "
"callable object can be used:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:593
msgid ""
">>> from vtkmodules.vtkCommonCore import vtkCommand, VTK_INT\n"
">>>\n"
">>> def onError(object, event, calldata):\n"
">>>     print('object: %s - event: %s - msg: %s' % (object.GetClassName(), "
"event, calldata))\n"
">>>\n"
">>> onError.CallDataType = VTK_INT\n"
">>>\n"
">>> lt = vtkLookupTable()\n"
">>> lt.AddObserver(vtkCommand.ErrorEvent, onError)\n"
"1\n"
">>> lt.SetTableRange(2,1)\n"
"object: vtkLookupTable - event: ErrorEvent - msg: ERROR:\n"
"In /home/user/VTK/Common/Core/vtkLookupTable.cxx, line 122\n"
"vtkLookupTable (0x6b40b30): Bad table range: [2, 1]\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:608
msgid ""
"For convenience, the `CallDataType` can also be specified where the function "
"is first declared with the help of the `@calldata_type` decorator:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:611
msgid ""
">>> from vtkmodules.util.misc import calldata_type\n"
">>>\n"
">>> @calldata_type(VTK_INT)\n"
">>> def onError(object, event, calldata):\n"
">>>     print('object: %s - event: %s - msg: %s' % (object.GetClassName(),\n"
"                                                    event, calldata))\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:618
msgid "Other Wrapped Entities"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:620
msgid "Constants"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:622
msgid ""
"Most of the constants defined in the VTK header files are available in "
"Python, and they can be accessed from the module in which they are defined.  "
"Many of these are found in the `vtkCommonCore` module, where they were "
"defined as preprocessor macros."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:627
msgid ""
">>> from vtkmodules.vtkCommonCore import VTK_DOUBLE_MAX\n"
">>> VTK_DOUBLE_MAX\n"
"1.0000000000000001e+299\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:631
msgid ""
"Others are defined as enums, often within a class namespace.  If the enum is "
"anonymous, then its values are `int`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:634
msgid ""
">>> vtkCommand.ErrorEvent\n"
"39\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:637
msgid ""
"Constants in the header files are wrapped if they are enums, or if they are "
"const variables of a wrappable scalar type, or if they are preprocessor "
"symbols that evaluate to integer, floating-point, or string literal types."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:641
msgid "Enum Types"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:643
msgid ""
"Each named enum type is wrapped as a new Python type, and members of the "
"enum are instances of that type.  This allows type checking for enum types:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:646
msgid ""
">>> from vtkmodules.vtkCommonColor import vtkColorSeries\n"
">>> vtkColorSeries.COOL\n"
"2\n"
">>> isinstance(vtkColorSeries.ColorSchemes, vtkColorSeries.COOL)\n"
">>> cs = vtkColorSeries()\n"
">>> cs.SetColorScheme(vtkColorSeries.COOL)\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:653
msgid ""
"Enum classes are wrapped in a manner similar to named enums, except that the "
"enum values are placed within the enum class namespace.  For example, "
"`vtkEventDataAction` is an enum class, with '`Press`' as a member:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:657
msgid ""
">>> from vtkmodules.vtkCommonCore import vtkEventDataAction\n"
">>> vtkEventDataAction.Press\n"
"1\n"
">>> isinstance(vtkEventDataAction.Press, vtkEventDataAction)\n"
"True\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:663
msgid ""
"In the first example, the `ColorSchemes` enum type and the `COOL` enum value "
"were both defined in the `vtkColorSeries` namespace.  In the second example, "
"the `vtkEventDataAction` enum class was defined in the module namespace, and "
"the `Press` value was defined in the enum class namespace."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:668
msgid ""
"Note that the VTK enum types behave like C++ enums, and not like the Python "
"enums types provided by the Python '`enum`' module.  In particular, all VTK "
"enum values can be used anywhere that an `int` can be used."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:672
msgid "Namespaces"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:674
msgid ""
"Namespaces are currently wrapped in a very limited manner.  The only "
"namespace members that are wrapped are enum constants and enum types. There "
"is no wrapping of namespaced classes or functions, or of nested namespaces.  "
"Currently, the wrappers implement namespaces as Python `module` objects."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:681
msgid "Docstrings"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:683
msgid ""
"The wrappers automatically generate docstrings from the doxygen comments in "
"the header files.  The Python `help()` command can be used to print the "
"documentation to the screen, or the `__doc__` attributes of the classes and "
"methods can be accessed directly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:688
msgid "Method Docstrings"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:690
msgid ""
"The method docstrings are formatted with the method signatures first, "
"followed by doxygen comments.  The Python method signatures have type "
"annotations, and are followed by the C++ method signatures for completeness."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:695
msgid ""
"    InvokeEvent(self, event:int, callData:Any) -> int\n"
"    C++: int InvokeEvent(unsigned long event, void* callData)\n"
"    InvokeEvent(self, event:str, callData:Any) -> int\n"
"    C++: int InvokeEvent(const char* event, void* callData)\n"
"    InvokeEvent(self, event:int) -> int\n"
"    C++: int InvokeEvent(unsigned long event)\n"
"    InvokeEvent(self, event:str) -> int\n"
"    C++: int InvokeEvent(const char* event)\n"
"\n"
"    This method invokes an event and returns whether the event was\n"
"    aborted or not. If the event was aborted, the return value is 1,\n"
"    otherwise it is 0.\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:710
msgid ""
"Some Python IDEs will automatically show the docstring as soon as you type "
"the name of the method."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:713
msgid "Class Docstrings"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:715
msgid ""
"The class docstrings include a brief description of the class, followed by "
"the name of the superclass, and then the full doxygen documentation, "
"including doxygen markup:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:719
msgid ""
"    vtkMatrix4x4 - represent and manipulate 4x4 transformation matrices\n"
"\n"
"    Superclass: vtkObject\n"
"\n"
"    vtkMatrix4x4 is a class to represent and manipulate 4x4 matrices.\n"
"    Specifically, it is designed to work on 4x4 transformation matrices\n"
"    found in 3D rendering using homogeneous coordinates [x y z w]. Many\n"
"    of the methods take an array of 16 doubles in row-major format. Note\n"
"    that OpenGL stores matrices in column-major format, so the matrix\n"
"    contents must be transposed when they are moved between OpenGL and\n"
"    VTK.\n"
"    @sa\n"
"    vtkTransform\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:735
msgid ""
"If the class is not derived from `vtkObjectBase`, then it will have one or "
"more public constructors, and these will be included before the comments:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:738
msgid ""
"    vtkSimpleCriticalSection() -> vtkSimpleCriticalSection\n"
"    C++: vtkSimpleCriticalSection()\n"
"    vtkSimpleCriticalSection(isLocked:int) -> vtkSimpleCriticalSection\n"
"    C++: vtkSimpleCriticalSection(int isLocked)\n"
"\n"
"    vtkSimpleCriticalSection - Critical section locking class\n"
"\n"
"    vtkCriticalSection allows the locking of variables which are accessed\n"
"    through different threads.\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:750
msgid "Template Docstrings"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:752
msgid ""
"Class templates are documented similar to classes, except that they include "
"a 'Provided Types' section that lists the available template instantiations "
"and the C++ template arguments that they correspond to."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:756
msgid ""
"    vtkSOADataArrayTemplate - Struct-Of-Arrays implementation of\n"
"    vtkGenericDataArray.\n"
"\n"
"    Superclass: vtkGenericDataArray[vtkSOADataArrayTemplate[ValueTypeT],"
"ValueTypeT]\n"
"\n"
"    vtkSOADataArrayTemplate is the counterpart of vtkAOSDataArrayTemplate.\n"
"    Each component is stored in a separate array.\n"
"\n"
"    @sa\n"
"    vtkGenericDataArray vtkAOSDataArrayTemplate\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"    Provided Types:\n"
"\n"
"      vtkSOADataArrayTemplate[char] => vtkSOADataArrayTemplate<char>\n"
"      vtkSOADataArrayTemplate[int8] => vtkSOADataArrayTemplate<signed char>\n"
"      vtkSOADataArrayTemplate[uint8] => vtkSOADataArrayTemplate<unsigned "
"char>\n"
"      vtkSOADataArrayTemplate[int16] => vtkSOADataArrayTemplate<short>\n"
"      vtkSOADataArrayTemplate[uint16] => vtkSOADataArrayTemplate<unsigned "
"short>\n"
"      vtkSOADataArrayTemplate[int32] => vtkSOADataArrayTemplate<int>\n"
"      vtkSOADataArrayTemplate[uint32] => vtkSOADataArrayTemplate<unsigned "
"int>\n"
"      vtkSOADataArrayTemplate[int] => vtkSOADataArrayTemplate<long>\n"
"      vtkSOADataArrayTemplate[uint] => vtkSOADataArrayTemplate<unsigned "
"long>\n"
"      vtkSOADataArrayTemplate[int64] => vtkSOADataArrayTemplate<long long>\n"
"      vtkSOADataArrayTemplate[uint64] => vtkSOADataArrayTemplate<unsigned "
"long long>\n"
"      vtkSOADataArrayTemplate[float32] => vtkSOADataArrayTemplate<float>\n"
"      vtkSOADataArrayTemplate[float64] => vtkSOADataArrayTemplate<double>\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:786
msgid ""
"Unlike classes, the template documentation is formatted similarly regardless "
"of whether the the class template derives from `vtkObjectBase` or not:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:789
msgid ""
"    vtkVector - templated base type for storage of vectors.\n"
"\n"
"    Superclass: vtkTuple[T,Size]\n"
"\n"
"    This class is a templated data type for storing and manipulating fixed\n"
"    size vectors, which can be used to represent two and three dimensional\n"
"    points. The memory layout is a contiguous array of the specified type,\n"
"    such that a float[2] can be cast to a vtkVector2f and manipulated. Also\n"
"    a float[6] could be cast and used as a vtkVector2f[3].\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"    Provided Types:\n"
"\n"
"      vtkVector[float64,4] => vtkVector<double, 4>\n"
"      vtkVector[float32,4] => vtkVector<float, 4>\n"
"      vtkVector[int32,4] => vtkVector<int, 4>\n"
"      vtkVector[float64,2] => vtkVector<double, 2>\n"
"      vtkVector[float32,2] => vtkVector<float, 2>\n"
"      vtkVector[int32,2] => vtkVector<int, 2>\n"
"      vtkVector[float64,3] => vtkVector<double, 3>\n"
"      vtkVector[float32,3] => vtkVector<float, 3>\n"
"      vtkVector[int32,3] => vtkVector<int, 3>\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:815
msgid "Internals and Advanced Topics"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:817
msgid "Special Attributes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:819
msgid ""
"Classes and objects derived from `vtkObjectBase` have special attributes, "
"which are only used in very special circumstances."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:822
msgid ""
"The `__vtkname__` attribute of the class provides the same string that the "
"GetClassName() method returns.  With the exception of classes that are "
"template instantiations, it is identical to the `__name__` attribute. For "
"template instantiations, however, `GetClassName()` and `__vtkname__` return "
"the result of calling `typeid(cls).name()` from C++, which provides a "
"platform specific result:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:829
msgid ""
">>> vtkSOADataArrayTemplate['float32'].__vtkname__\n"
"'23vtkSOADataArrayTemplateIfE'\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:832
msgid ""
"This can be used to get the VTK `ClassName` when you don't have an "
"instantiation to call `GetClassName()` on.  It is useful for checking the "
"type of a C++ VTK object against a Python VTK class."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:836
msgid ""
"The `__this__` attribute of the objects is a bit less esoteric, it provides "
"a pointer to the C++ object as a mangled string:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:839
msgid ""
">>> a = vtkFloatArray()\n"
">>> a.__this__\n"
"'_00005653a6a6f700_p_vtkFloatArray'\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:843
msgid ""
"The string provides the hexadecimal address of '`this`', followed by "
"'`p`' (shorthand for *pointer*), and the type of the pointer.  You can also "
"construct a Python object directly from the C++ address, if the address is "
"formatted as described above:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:848
msgid ""
">>> a = vtkFloatArray('_00005653a6a6f700_p_vtkFloatArray')\n"
">>> a\n"
"<vtkmodules.vtkCommonCore.vtkFloatArray(0x5653a6a6f700) at 0x7f0e7aecf5e0>\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:852
msgid ""
"If you call the constructor on the string provided by `__this__`, you will "
"get exactly the same Python object back again, rather than a new object. But "
"this constructor can be useful if you have some VTK code that has been "
"wrapped with a different wrapper tool, for example with SWIG.  If you can "
"get the VTK pointer from SWIG, you can use it to construct Python object "
"that can be used with the native VTK wrappers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:859
msgid "Wrapper Hints"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:861
msgid ""
"A wrapper hint is an attribute that can be added to a class, method, or "
"parameter declaration in a C++ header file to give extra information to the "
"wrappers.  These hints are defined in the `vtkWrappingHints.h` header file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:866
msgid "The following hints can appear before a method declaration:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:867
msgid "`VTK_WRAPEXCLUDE` excludes a method from the wrappers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:868
msgid ""
"`VTK_NEWINSTANCE` passes ownership of a method's return value to the caller"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:870
msgid ""
"For convenience, `VTK_WRAPEXCLUDE` can also be used to exclude a whole "
"class. The `VTK_NEWINSTANCE` hint is used when the return value is a "
"`vtkObjectBase*` and the caller must not increment the reference count upon "
"acceptance of the object (but must still decrement the reference count when "
"finished with the object)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:876
msgid "The following hints can appear after a method declaration:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:877
msgid "`VTK_EXPECTS(cond)` provides preconditions for the method call"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:878
msgid "`VTK_SIZEHINT(expr)` marks the array size of a return value"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:879
msgid "`VTK_SIZEHINT(name, expr)` marks the array size of a parameter"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:881
msgid ""
"For `VTK_EXPECTS(cond)`, the precondition must be valid C++ code, and can "
"use any of the parameter names or `this`.  Even without `this`, any public "
"names in the class namespace (including method names) will be resolved. See "
"the [Preconditions](#preconditions) section for additional information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:886
msgid ""
"`VTK_SIZEHINT(expr)` is used for methods that return an array as type `T*`, "
"where `T` is a numeric data type.  The hint allows the wrappers to convert "
"the array to a tuple of the correct size.  Without the size hint, the "
"wrappers will return the pointer as a string that provides a mangled memory "
"address of the form '`_hhhhhhhhhhhh_p_void`' where '`hhhhhhhhhhhh`' is "
"address expressed in hexadecimal."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:893
msgid ""
"`VTK_SIZEHINT(parameter_name, expr)` is used to hint parameters of type `T*` "
"or `T&*` (with `T` as a numeric data type) so that the wrappers know the "
"size of the array that the pointer is pointing to.  The `expr` can be any "
"expression that evaluates to an integer, and it can include parameter names, "
"public class members and method calls, or the special name `_` (underscore) "
"which indicates the method's return value.  In the absence of a size hint, "
"the wrappers cannot check that the length of the sequence passed from Python "
"matches the size of the array required by the method. If the method requires "
"a larger array than it receives, a buffer overrun will occur."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:904
msgid "The following hints can appear before a parameter declaration:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:905
msgid "`VTK_FILEPATH` marks a parameter that accepts a pathlib.Path object"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:906
msgid "`VTK_ZEROCOPY` marks a parameter that accepts a buffer object"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:908
msgid ""
"More specifically, `VTK_FILEPATH` is used with `char*` and `std::string` "
"parameters to indicate that the method also accepts any object with a "
"`__fspath__()` method that returns a path string.  And `VTK_ZEROCOPY` is "
"used with `T*` parameters, for basic integer or float type `T`, to indicate "
"that the Python buffer protocol will be used to access the values, rather "
"than the Python sequence protocol that is used by default."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:915
msgid "Deprecation Warnings"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:917
msgid ""
"In addition to the wrapping hints, the Python wrappers are also aware of the "
"deprecation attributes that have been applied to classes and methods.  When "
"a deprecated method is called, a `DeprecationWarning` is generated and "
"information about the deprecation is printed, including the VTK version for "
"the deprecation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:923
msgid "To ignore these warnings, use the following code:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:925
msgid ""
"import warnings\n"
"warnings.filterwarnings('ignore', category=DeprecationWarning)\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:928
msgid "To see each deprecation warning just once per session,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:930
msgid "warnings.filterwarnings('once', category=DeprecationWarning)\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:932
msgid "Template Keys"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:934
msgid ""
"The following is a table of common template key names, which are the same as "
"the numpy dtype names.  Note that you can actually use numpy dtypes as keys, "
"as well as the native Python types `bool`, `int`, and `float`.  There is "
"some danger in using `int`, however, because it maps to C++ `long` which has "
"a platform-dependent size (either 32 bits or 64 bits).  Finally, the char "
"codes from the Python `array` module can be used as keys, but they should be "
"avoided since more programmers are familiar with numpy than with the much "
"older `array` module."
msgstr ""

