#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:963
msgid "Exception Handling"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:965
msgid ""
"There are times when an observer might generate a Python exception.  Since "
"the observers are called from C++, there is no good way to catch these "
"exceptions from within Python.  So, instead, the wrappers simply print a "
"traceback to stderr and then clear the error indicator.  The Python program "
"will continue running unless the exception was a `KeyboardInterrupt` (Ctrl-"
"C), in which case the program will exit with an error code of 1."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:972
msgid "Deleting a vtkObject"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:974
msgid ""
"There is no direct equivalent of VTK's `Delete()` method, since Python does "
"garbage collection automatically.  The Python object will be deleted when "
"there are no references to it within Python, and the C++ object will be "
"deleted when there are no references to it from within either Python or C++. "
"Note that references can hide in unexpected places, for example if a method "
"of an object is used as an observer callback, the object will not be deleted "
"until the observer is disconnected."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:982
msgid ""
"The `DeleteEvent` can be used to detect object deletion, but note that the "
"observer will receive a None for the object, since the observer is called "
"after (not before) the deletion occurs:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:986
msgid ""
">>> o = vtkObject()\n"
">>> o.AddObserver('DeleteEvent', lambda o,e: print(e, o))\n"
"1\n"
">>> del o\n"
"DeleteEvent None\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:992
msgid ""
"If you need to know what object is deleted, the identifying information must "
"be extracted before the deletion occurs:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:995
msgid ""
">>> o = vtkObject()\n"
">>> o.AddObserver('DeleteEvent',lambda x,e,r=repr(o): print(e, r))\n"
"1\n"
">>> del o\n"
"DeleteEvent <vtkmodules.vtkCommonCore.vtkObject(0x55783870f970) at "
"0x7f1e61678be0>\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:1001
msgid ""
"In cases where you need to track down tricky memory issues, you might find "
"it useful to call the `GetReferenceCount()` method of the object directly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:1004
msgid "Ghosts"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:1006
msgid ""
"A wrapped VTK object (derived from `vtkObjectBase`) is a Python object that "
"holds a pointer to a C++ object (specifically, a `vtkObjectBase*`).  The "
"Python object can have attributes that the C++ object knows nothing about. "
"So, what happens to these attributes if the Python object is deleted, but "
"the C++ object lives on?  Consider this simple example of storing the C++ "
"object in an array and then deleting the Python object:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:1013
msgid ""
"obj = vtkObject()\n"
"obj.tag = 'FirstObject'\n"
"va = vtkVariantArray()\n"
"va.InsertNextValue(obj)\n"
"del obj\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:1019
msgid ""
"When we retrieve the object from the array, we want it to have the '`tag`' "
"attributes that it had we stored it.  But you might wonder, aren't all "
"Python-specific attributes deleted along with the Python object?  The answer "
"is, no they aren't, they're saved until until the C++ object itself is "
"deleted."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:1025
msgid ""
"The wrappers have a special place, which we will call the graveyard, where "
"'ghosts' of objects are stored when the objects are deleted. The ghost is "
"not an object, but rather a container for the Python attributes of a "
"deceased object.  If the object ever reappears within Python, usually as a "
"return value from a C++ method call, then the ghost is resurrected as a new "
"Python object that has all the attributes of the original Python object."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:1032
msgid ""
"The graveyard is only used for objects that have unfinished business.  If a "
"Python object has an empty dict and no other special attributes, then it "
"will not go to the graveyard.  Also, if the C++ object is deleted at the "
"same time as the Python object, then the graveyard will not be used.  Each "
"ghost in the graveyard holds a weak pointer to its C++ object and will "
"vanish when the C++ object is deleted (not immediately, but the next time "
"the graveyard garbage collector runs)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:1040
msgid "Subclassing a VTK Class"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:1042
msgid ""
"It is possible to subclass a VTK class from within Python, but this is of "
"limited use because the C++ virtual methods are not hooked to the Python "
"methods.  In other words, if you make a subclass of `vtkPolyDataAlgorithm` "
"and override the `Execute()` method, it will not be automatically called by "
"the VTK pipeline. Your `Execute()` method will only be called if the call is "
"made from Python."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:1049
msgid ""
"The addition of virtual method hooks to the wrappers has been proposed, but "
"currently the only way for Python methods to be called from C++ code is via "
"callbacks. The `vtkProgrammableSource` and `vtkProgrammableFilter` are "
"examples of VTK algorithm classes that use callbacks for execution, while "
"`vtkInteractionStyleUser` can use observer callbacks for event handling."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:1055
msgid "Wrapping External VTK Modules"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:1057
msgid ""
"If you have your own C++ classes that are based on VTK, and if they are "
"placed with a VTK module with a vtk.module file, then they can be wrapped as "
"shown in the [Module Wrapping Example][external-wrapping].  You will also "
"find the cmake documentation on VTK modules to be useful."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:1064
msgid "Runtime C++ object wrapping"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:1066
msgid ""
"VTK allows to declare an object in C++ and to use it in Python. To do so, "
"you can simply call `vtkPythonUtil::GetObjectFromPointer` which will create "
"your Python object from the pointer to a C++ VTK object. Here is a minimal "
"example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:1070
msgid ""
"  #include <vtkPythonInterpreter.h>\n"
"  #include <vtkPythonUtil.h>\n"
"  #include <vtkSmartPyObject.h>\n"
"\n"
"  ...\n"
"\n"
"  // Create a C++ object\n"
"  vtkNew<vtkPolyData> data;\n"
"\n"
"  // Initialize interpreter and GIL\n"
"  vtkPythonInterpreter::Initialize();\n"
"  vtkPythonScopeGilEnsurer gilEnsurer(true, true);\n"
"\n"
"  // Import vtk in Python\n"
"  vtkPythonInterpreter::RunSimpleString(\"import vtkmodules."
"vtkCommonCore\");\n"
"\n"
"  // Create the python object from the C++ object\n"
"  vtkSmartPyObject pyDataFromCpp;\n"
"  pyDataFromCpp.TakeReference(vtkPythonUtil::GetObjectFromPointer(data."
"GetPointer()));\n"
"\n"
"  // Make it visible from python\n"
"  PyObject* mainModule = PyImport_AddModule(\"__main__\");\n"
"  PyObject* mainDict = PyModule_GetDict(mainModule);\n"
"  PyDict_SetItemString(mainDict, \"pyDataFromPython\", pyDataFromCpp)\n"
"\n"
"  // Run Python script\n"
"  std::string script;\n"
"  script += \"print(type(pyDataFromPython))\\n\"; // available with the name "
"set above\n"
"  vtkPythonInterpreter::RunSimpleString(script.c_str());\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:1102
msgid "Experimental Features"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:1104
msgid "Python Class Overrides"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:1106
msgid ""
"VTK now supports overriding wrapped classes with Python subclasses.  This "
"enables developers to provide more Python friendly interfaces for certain "
"classes.  Here is a trivial example of an override:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:1110
msgid ""
"from vtkmodules.vtkCommonCore import vtkPoints\n"
"@vtkPoints.override\n"
"class CustomPoints(vtkPoints):\n"
"    pass\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:1115
msgid ""
"Once the override is in place, any future `vtkPoints` Python object "
"instances will be instances of the override class.  This behavior is global."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:1118
msgid "points = vtk.vtkPoints() # returns an instance of CustomPoints\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:1120
msgid ""
"The override can be reversed by setting an override of `None`, but this will "
"not impact instantiations that have already occurred."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:1123
msgid "vtkPoints.override(None)\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:1125
msgid ""
"If a class is already overridden in C++ via VTK's object factory mechanism, "
"for example the vtkWin32OpenGLRenderWindow override for vtkRenderWindow, "
"then directly applying a Python override to the original class will not "
"work.  However, the Python override can be chained to the C++ override "
"class. For example, here is a chained override of vtkRenderWindow on Windows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:1131
msgid ""
"@vtkWin32OpenGLRenderWindow.override\n"
"class CustomRenderWindow(vtkWin32OpenGLRenderWindow):\n"
"    ...\n"
"window = vtkRenderWindow() # creates a CustomRenderWindow\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:1136
msgid ""
"Please see [Subclassing a VTK Class](#subclassing-a-vtk-class) for "
"additional restrictions on subclassing VTK classes through Python."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:1139
msgid "Overrides and initialization"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:1141
msgid ""
"The previous section contained examples of when an overridden VTK class is "
"instantiated in Python.  A more interesting case is when the overridden "
"class is instantiated in C++ and then, sometime later, becomes visible to "
"the Python interpreter:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:1146
msgid ""
"from vtkmodules.vtkImagingSources import vtkImageGridSource\n"
"from vtkmodules.vtkCommonDataModel import vtkImageData\n"
"\n"
"@vtkImageData.override\n"
"class CustomImageData(vtkImageData):\n"
"    def __init__(self, filename=None):\n"
"        self.filename = filename\n"
"\n"
"source = vtkImageGridSource()\n"
"source.SetDataSpacing(0.1, 0.1, 0.1)\n"
"source.Update()\n"
"data = source.GetOutput()\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:1159
msgid ""
"In this example, the vtkImageData object is created by vtkImageGridSource. "
"At the time of its creation, it is a C++ object and Python is unaware that "
"it has been created.  The corresponding Python object is not created until "
"`source.GetOutput()` is called and returns the object.  It is specifically "
"at this point that the override mechanism kicks in.  The C++ object remains "
"the same, but the Python wrapper around that object is instantiated from the "
"override class.  This exemplifies the dual nature of VTK-Python objects."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:1167
msgid ""
"The automatic creation of the Python wrapper object is usually transparent, "
"and is something that we take for granted.  However, one must be aware that "
"the creation of the wrapper object involves calling its `__init__()` method, "
"which can have unwanted side-effects if the C++ object itself is no longer "
"in its initial state.  In the example above, the vtkImageData object will "
"already have been modified by the vtkImageGridSource before the `__init__()` "
"method adds the new `filename` attribute."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:1175
msgid ""
"A situation that we want to avoid, and which is only possible for override "
"classes, is when the Python `__init__()` method modifies attributes of the "
"pre-existing C++ object:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:1179
msgid ""
"@vtkImageData.override\n"
"class CustomImageData(vtkImageData):\n"
"    def __init__(self, spacing=(1.0, 1.0, 1.0)):\n"
"        self.SetSpacing(spacing)\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:1184
msgid ""
"Even though the vtkImageData object has already had its C++ attributes set "
"by the vtkImageGridSource prior to the call to `__init__()`, this override "
"will forcibly reset the spacing upon the call to `source.GetOutput()`.  This "
"is not what we want!  In fact, the Python wrappers will raise a RuntimError "
"warning when this occurs:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:1190
msgid ""
">>> data = source.GetOutput()\n"
"RuntimeWarning: Python method CustomImageData.__init__() unexpectedly\n"
"modified pre-existing C++ base object vtkImageData (0x563cf7ddaf20).\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:1194
msgid ""
"During the automated creation of a Python wrapper for a pre-existing C++ "
"object, `__init__()` is always called with no parameters, so the goal is to "
"ensure that default construction never modifies the C++ object.  This can be "
"done by making all modifications conditional:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:1199
msgid ""
"@vtkImageData.override\n"
"class CustomImageData(vtkImageData):\n"
"    def __init__(self, spacing=None):\n"
"        if spacing is not None:\n"
"            self.SetSpacing(spacing)\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:1205
msgid "Stub Files for Type Hinting"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:1207
msgid ""
"VTK includes a script called [`generate_pyi.py`][generate_pyi] that will "
"generate pyi stub files for each wrapped VTK module.  The purpose of these "
"files, as explained in [PEP 484][pep_484], is to provide type information "
"for all constants, classes, and methods in the modules. Each of these files "
"contain blocks like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:1213
msgid ""
"VTK_DOUBLE:int\n"
"VTK_DOUBLE_MAX:float\n"
"VTK_DOUBLE_MIN:float\n"
"...\n"
"\n"
"class vtkObject(vtkObjectBase):\n"
"    def AddObserver(self, event:int, command:Callback, priority:float=0.0) -"
"> int: ...\n"
"    def GetMTime(self) -> int: ...\n"
"    @staticmethod\n"
"    def GetNumberOfGenerationsFromBaseType(type:str) -> int: ...\n"
"    @overload\n"
"    def HasObserver(self, event:int, __b:'vtkCommand') -> int: ...\n"
"    @overload\n"
"    def HasObserver(self, event:str, __b:'vtkCommand') -> int: ...\n"
"\n"
"class vtkAbstractArray(vtkObject):\n"
"    class DeleteMethod(int): ...\n"
"    VTK_DATA_ARRAY_ALIGNED_FREE:'DeleteMethod'\n"
"    VTK_DATA_ARRAY_DELETE:'DeleteMethod'\n"
"    VTK_DATA_ARRAY_FREE:'DeleteMethod'\n"
"    VTK_DATA_ARRAY_USER_DEFINED:'DeleteMethod'\n"
"    def Allocate(self, numValues:int, ext:int=1000) -> int: ...\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:1236
msgid ""
"Python consoles like ipython and IDEs like PyCharm can use the information "
"in these files to provide hints while you edit the code.  These files are "
"included in the Python packages for VTK, but they can also be built by "
"executing the `generate_pyi.py` script.  To do so, execute the script with "
"the `vtkpython` executable (or with the regular python executable, if its "
"paths are set for VTK):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:1243
msgid "vtkpython -m vtkmodules.generate_pyi\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:1245
msgid ""
"This will place build the pyi files and place them inside the `vtkmodules` "
"package, where ipython and PyCharm should automatically find them.  The help "
"for this script is as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:1249
msgid ""
"usage: python generate_pyi.py [-p package] [-o output_dir] [module ...]\n"
"options:\n"
"  -p NAME        Package name [vtkmodules by default].\n"
"  -o OUTPUT      Output directory [package directory by default].\n"
"  -e EXT         Output file suffix [.pyi by default].\n"
"  module         Module or modules to process [all by default].\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/PythonWrappers.md:1256
msgid ""
"The pyi files are syntactically correct python files, so it is possible to "
"load them as such in order to test them and inspect them."
msgstr ""
